  "why": "The paper describes and implements explicit design choices intended to produce transferable failures and it empirically demonstrates cross-model transferability. Concretely, CAGFuzz's adversarial example generator (AEG) is trained on general (dataset-level) domains rather than on a specific target model, deep-feature similarity is enforced to preserve semantics, and a separate public surrogate model is used to drive neuron-coverage selection (i.e., feedback from a surrogate during fuzzing). The authors then evaluate transferability across multiple target models and report that CAGFuzz-generated examples improve accuracy and reveal errors across different model instances (Tables 3/4 and the RQ1 discussion). These elements together satisfy the metric's requirement for explicit mechanisms to support discovery of transferable failures and demonstration of cross-model transferability.",
